{{Orphan|date=February 2018}}
{{Infobox scientist | name = Anna Coutsoudis | image = | image_size = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1952|09|21}} | nationality = [[South Africa]] | fields = [[Public health]] | workplaces = [[University of KwaZulu-Natal]] | alma_mater = [[University of Natal]] | awards = | website = }}
'''Anna Coutsoudis''' (born 21 September 1952) is a South African [[Public health|public health scientist]] and academic who has conducted research on [[HIV]] and [[nutrition]], specializing in the benefits of [[breastfeeding]]. An elected member of the [[Academy of Science of South Africa]], she is a founder member and chair of iThemba Lethu, an organization for children with HIV, which provides a community-based breast milk bank.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.assaf.org.za/index.php/about-assaf/members|title=Members|publisher=Academy of Science of South Africa|accessdate=18 October 2017 |language=}}</ref><ref name=dpch>{{cite web|url=http://paediatrics.ukzn.ac.za/Staff/ProfAnnaCoutsoudis.aspx|title=Prof Anna Coutsoudis|publisher= Department of Paediatrics & Child Health, University of KwaZulu-Natal|accessdate=18 October 2017 |language=}}</ref>
==Biography== Coutsoudis received her BSc from the [[University of Natal]] in 1974, followed by a Higher Diploma in Education in 1975.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://whoswho.co.za/anna-coutsoudis-5057|title=Anna Coutsoudis|publisher=Who's Who Southern Africa|accessdate=18 October 2017 |language=}}</ref> Later, while raising a family, she completed her studies at the same university, earning a PhD from the Department of Paediatrics and Child Health with a thesis titled ''Epidemiological and clinical studies of vitamin A in Black South African pre-school children''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://oatd.org/oatd/record?record=handle%5C:10413%5C%2F7451&q=%2A%3A%2A|title=Epidemiological and clinical studies of vitamin A in Black South African pre-school children|author=Coutsoudis, Anna|publisher=Open Access Theses and Dissertations|year=1993|accessdate=18 October 2017 |language=}}</ref><ref name=asgm>{{cite web|url=http://chs.ukzn.ac.za/news/09-10-22/ACADEMY_OF_SCIENCE_GOLD_MEDAL_FOR_PROMINENT_UKZN_SCIENTIST.aspx|title=Academy of Science Gold Medal for Prominent UKZN Scientist |publisher=University of KwaZulu-Natal|date=22 October 2009|accessdate=18 October 2017 |language=}}</ref>
She was honoured by an award from [[La Leche League International]] in 2001 for stressing the benefits of breastfeeding while in 2004 her extensive work on nutrition research was recognized by the Nutrition Society of South Africa.<ref name=asgm/>
In Mexico at the [[International AIDS Society]] Conference in 2008, Coutsoudis presented a convincing and well-received paper which stressed the benefits of breastfeeding for HIV-affected infants.<ref name="Susser2011">{{cite book|last=Susser|first=Ida|title=AIDS, Sex, and Culture: Global Politics and Survival in Southern Africa|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qaeg6RqZb0YC&pg=RA1-PA1951|year=2011|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-1-4443-5910-7|pages=1–}}</ref> The following year, an article she and her colleague [[Hoosen Coovadia]] published in ''[[The Lancet]]'' called on the South African government to stop providing free formula milk to HIV-infected mothers, causing outrage from HIV activists. In particular, Cousoudis criticized the commercial promotion of formula milk for young babies in South Africa, especially as it countered recommendations from the [[World Health Organization]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mg.co.za/article/2009-08-25-professors-provoke-breastfeeding-outrage|title=Professors provoke breastfeeding outrage|publisher=''Mail & Guardian''|author=Barrett, Sara|date=25 August 2009|accessdate=18 October 2017 |language=}}</ref> In September 2016, Coutsoudis participated in the [[International Atomic Energy Agency]]'s 60th conference in [[Vienna]] where she was a key speaker at a well-attended event on "Nuclear Techniques to Assess Breastfeeding Practices".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ndaba-online.ukzn.ac.za/UkzndabaStory/162/nuclear-techniques-to-assess-breastfeeding-practices-/#sthash.mF8XN9XN.dpbs|title=Nuclear Techniques to Assess Breastfeeding Practices |publisher=University of KwaZulu-Natal: UKZNDADA online|author=Francis, MaryAnn|date=13 October 2016|accessdate=19 October 2017 |language=}}</ref>
Coutsoudis has served on various committees of the World Health Organizaion including the Steering Committee of the Child and Adolescent Health Unit and guideline development groups on [[Vitamin A]] Supplementation and HIV and Infant Feeding.<ref name=dpch/> She has published over 100 [[Peer review|peer-reviewed]] scientific articles.<ref>USA, Gov. [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=Coutsoudis+A%5BAuthor%5D "NCBI - Coutsoudis A author search"], ''PubMed'', Baltimore, 18 October 2017.</ref>
==Awards and honors== In 2009, Anna Coutsoudis was awarded the Science for Society Gold Medal by the Academy of Science of South Africa.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.twas-rossa.org.za/network/item/1-twas-fellows/20-coutsoudis-anna|title=Coutsoudis, Anna|publisher=TWAS-Rossa: The World Academy of Sciences Regional Office for sub-Saharan Africa|accessdate=18 October 2017 |language=}}</ref>
