{{Infobox NRHP | name = Secondary Industrial School | nrhp_type = | image = SecondaryIndustrialSchoolColumbusGAFrontStraightOn.JPG | caption = | location= 1112 29th St., [[Columbus, Georgia]] | coordinates = {{coord|32|29|21|N|84|58|41|W|source:NRIS2013a|name=Secondary Industrial School|display=inline,title}} | locmapin = USA Georgia | built = 1906 | architect= [[J.W. Golucke & Co.]] | architecture = [[Beaux Arts architecture|Beaux Arts]] | added = April 9, 1980 | area = {{convert|4.2|acre}} | refnum = 80001199<ref name="nris">{{NRISref|version=2013a}}</ref> }} The '''Secondary Industrial School''' in [[Columbus, Georgia]] is a historic school built in 1906. It was the first secondary-level industrial/vocational school in the United States: it "has been called the nation's first public-supported, coeducational industrial high school."<ref name=nrhpdoc/> Located at 1112 29th St., the building was designed by [[J.W. Golucke & Co.]] in [[Beaux Arts architecture|Beaux Arts]] style. It was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1980.<ref name=nris/>
It has also been known as '''S.I.S.''', as '''Columbus Junior High''', and as '''Jordan Vocational High'''.
It was a project of [[Carleton B. Gibson]], who became Superintendent of schools in Columbus in 1896.<ref name="nrhpdoc">{{cite web|url={{NRHP url|id=80001199}}|title=National Register of Historic Places Inventory/Nomination: Secondary Industrial School / Columbus Junior High, 1939; currently Jordan Vocational Night School |publisher=[[National Park Service]]|author=Kenneth H. Thomas, Jr. |author2=Richard R. Cloues |date=January 11, 1980 |accessdate=June 25, 2018}} With {{NRHP url|id=80001199|photos=y|title=accompanying 10 photos from 1979}}</ref>
==See also== *[[Harrison-Gibson House]], home of Gibson, also NRHP-listed
